uel/hoplite#preprocessors) that will\n28:  replace placeholders with values resolved from external configs, such as AWS Secrets Manager, Azure KeyVault and so on.\n29-- **Reloadable config:** Trigger config [reloads](#reloadable-config) on a fixed interval or in response to external\n30-  events such as consul value changes.\n--\n41-\n42-```groovy\n43:implementation 'com.sksamuel.hoplite:hoplite-core:<version>'\n44-```\n45-\n--\n49-You should create a top level class which can be named simply Config, or ProjectNameConfig. This class then defines a field for each config value you need. It can include nested data classes for grouping together related configs.\n50-\n51:For example, if we had a project that needed database config, config for an embedded HTTP server, and a field which contained which environment we were running in (staging, QA, production etc), then we may define our classes like this:\n52-\n53-```kotlin\n--\n57-```\n58-\n59:For our staging environment, we may create a YAML (or Json, etc) file called `application-staging.yaml`.\n60-The name doesn't matter, you can use any convention you wish.\n61-\n--\n77-\n78-```kotlin\n79:val config = ConfigLoaderBuilder.default()\n80:               .addResourceSource(\"/application-staging.yml\")\n81-               .build()\n82-               .loadConfigOrThrow<Config>()\n--\n95-enable reports, add preprocessors and more.\n96-\n97:To create a default builder, use `ConfigLoaderBuilder.default()` and after adding your sources, call `build`.\n98-Here is an example:\n99-\n100-```kotlin\n101:ConfigLoaderBuilder.default()\n102:  .addResourceSource(\"/application-prod.yml\")\n103:  .addResourceSource(\"/reference.json\")\n104-  .build()\n105-  .loadConfigOrThrow<MyConfig>()\n--\n142-\n143-```kotlin\n144:val configBinder = ConfigLoaderBuilder.default()\n145:  .addResourceSource(\"/application-prod.yml\")\n146:  .addResourceSource(\"/reference.json\")\n147-  .build()\n148-  .configBinder()\n--\n194-```\n195-\n196:## Supported Formats\n197-\n198-Hoplite supports config files in several formats. You can mix and match formats if you really want to.\n--\n202-| Format                                                              | Module                                                             | File Extensions     |\n203-|:--------------------------------------------------------------------|:-------------------------------------------------------------------|:--------------------|\n204:| [Json](https://www.json.org/)                                       | [`hoplite-json`](https://search.maven.org/search?q=hoplite-json)   | .json               |\n205:| [Yaml](https://yaml.org/) Note: Yaml files are limited 3mb in size. | [`hoplite-yaml`](https://search.maven.org/search?q=hoplite-yaml)   | .yml, .yaml         |\n206-| [Toml](https://github.com/toml-lang/toml)                           | [`hoplite-toml`](https://search.maven.org/search?q=hoplite-toml)   | .toml               |\n207-| [Hocon](https://github.com/lightbend/config)                        | [`hoplite-hocon`](https://search.maven.org/search?q=hoplite-hocon) | .conf               |\n208:| Java Properties files                                               | built-in                                                           | .props, .properties |\n209-\n210-If you wish to add another format you can extend `Parser` and provide an instance of that implementation to\n--\n215-like this:\n216-\n217:`ConfigLoaderBuilder.default().addParser(\"data\", YamlParser).build()`\n218-\n219-### Note: fatJar/shadowJar\n--\n235-### EnvironmentVariablesPropertySource\n236-\n237:The `EnvironmentVariablesPropertySource` reads config from environment variables.\n238:This property source maps environment variable names to config properties via idiomatic conventions for environment variables.\n239:Env vars are idiomatically UPPERCASE and [contain only](https://pubs.opengroup.org/onlinepubs/000095399/basedefs/xbd_chap08.html) letters (`A` to `Z`), digits (`0` to `9`), and the underscore (`_`) character.\n240-\n241:Hoplite's binding rules align with [Spring Boot's relaxed binding for environment variables](https://docs.spring.io/spring-boot/reference/features/external-config.html#features.external-config.typesafe-configuration-properties.relaxed-binding.environment-variables) so that the same env vars can drive both kinds of app:\n242-\n243-| Rule | Env var | Binds to |\n244-|------|---------|----------|\n245:| Dots in property paths become underscores | `TOPIC_NAME` | `topic.name` |\n246-| Matching is case-insensitive — env vars uppercase, fields can be camelCase | `SPRING_MAIN_LOGSTARTUPINFO` | `spring.main.logStartupInfo` |\n247:| Dashes in property paths are removed (not replaced with underscores) | `LOGSTARTUPINFO` | `log-startup-info` (e.g. via `@ConfigAlias`) |\n248:| List/array indices are surrounded by underscores | `ITEMS_0`, `ITEMS_1` | `items: List<String>` |\n249-| List of nested objects | `SERVICE_0_OTHER`, `SERVICE_1_OTHER` | `service: List<Service(other = ...)>` |\n250-| Trailing path segment names a map key | `LABELS_ENV`, `LABELS_REGION` | `labels: Map<String, String>` |\n--\n264-### SystemPropertiesPropertySource\n265-\n266:The `SystemPropertiesPropertySource` provides config through system properties that are prefixed with `config.override.`.\n267-For example, starting your JVM with `-Dconfig.override.database.name` would override a config key of `database.name` residing in a file.\n268-\n269-The prefix may be customized by passing a `prefix` argument to the constructor, or set to an empty string to expose\n270:all system properties.\n271-\n272-\n--\n297-\n298-```kotlin\n299:ConfigLoaderBuilder.default()\n300:   .addResourceSource(\"/config.json\")\n301-   .build()\n302-   .loadConfigOrThrow<MyConfig>()\n--\n306-\n307-```kotlin\n308:ConfigLoaderBuilder.default()\n309:  .addResourceSource(\"/missing.yml\", optional = true)\n310:  .addResourceSource(\"/config.json\")\n311-  .build()\n312-  .loadConfigOrThrow<MyConfig>()\n--\n319-\n320-```kotlin\n321:ConfigLoaderBuilder.default()\n322-   .addSource(JsonPropertySource(\"\"\" { \"database\": \"localhost\", \"port\": 1234 } \"\"\"))\n323-   .build()\n--\n330-\n331-```kotlin\n332:ConfigLoaderBuilder.default()\n333-   .addSource(YamlPropertySource(\n334-     \"\"\"\n--\n345-\n346-```kotlin\n347:ConfigLoaderBuilder.default()\n348-  .addSource(TomlPropertySource(\n349-    \"\"\"\n--\n360-\n361-```kotlin\n362:ConfigLoaderBuilder.default()\n363-  .addSource(PropsPropertySource(myProps))\n364-  .build()\n--\n468-\n469-```kotlin\n470:ConfigLoaderBuilder.default()\n471:  .addResourceSource(\"/config-prd.yml\", true)\n472:  .addResourceSource(\"/config.yml\")\n473-  .strict()\n474-  .build()\n--\n612-| **Arrow**                               | Requires `hoplite-arrow` module                                                                                                                                                                             |\n613-| `arrow.data.NonEmptyList<A>`            | Converts arrays into a `NonEmptyList<A>` if the array is non empty. If the array is empty then an error is raised.                                                                                          |\n614:| `arrow.core.Option<A>`                  | A `None` is used for null or undefined values, and present values are converted to a `Some<A>`.                                                                                                             |\n615:| `arrow.core.Tuple2<A,B>`                | Converts an array of two elements into an instance of `Tuple2<A,B>`.  Will fail if the array does not have exactly two elements.                                                                            |\n616:| `arrow.core.Tuple3<A,B,C>`              | Converts an array of three elements into an instance of `Tuple3<A,B,C>`. Will fail if the array does not have exactly three elements.                                                                       |\n617:| `arrow.core.Tuple4<A,B,C,D>`            | Converts an array of four elements into an instance of `Tuple4<A,B,C,D>`. Will fail if the array does not have exactly four elements.                                                                       |\n618:| `arrow.core.Tuple5<A,B,C,D,E>`          | Converts an array of five elements into an instance of `Tuple5<A,B,C,D,E>`. Will fail if the array does not have exactly five elements.                                                                     |\n619-| **Hikari Connection Pool**              | Requires `hoplite-hikaricp` module                                                                                                                                                                          |\n620-| `HikariDataSource`                      | Converts nested config into a `HikariDataSource`. Any keys nested under the field name will be passed through to the `HikariConfig` object as the datasource is created. Requires `hoplite-hikaricp` module |\n--\n627-| `kotlinx.datetime.LocalDate`            |                                                                                                                                                                                                             |\n628-| `kotlinx.datetime.Instant`              |                                                                                                                                                                                                             |\n629:| **AWS SDK types**                       | Requires `hoplite-aws` module                                                                                                                                                                               |\n630-| `com.amazonaws.regions.Region`          |                                                                                                                                                                                                             |\n631-| **Micrometer types**                    | Requires `hoplite-micrometer-xxx` modules                                                                                                                                                                   |\n--\n666-The preprocessor is able to transform the value (or return the input - aka identity function) depending on the logic of that preprocessor.\n667-\n668:For example, a preprocessor may choose to perform environment variable substitution, configure default values,\n669-perform database lookups, or whatever other custom action you need when the config is being resolved.\n670-\n--\n694-| Preprocessor                   | Function                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                |\n695-|:-------------------------------|:----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|\n696:| `EnvVarPreprocessor`           | Replaces any strings of the form ${VAR} with the environment variable $VAR if defined. These replacement strings can occur between other strings.<br/><br/>For example `foo: hello ${USERNAME}` would result in foo being assigned the value `hello Sam` assuming the env var `USERNAME` was set to `SAM`. Also the expressions can have default values using the usual bash expression style syntax `foo: hello ${USERNAME:-fallback}` |\n697-| `SystemPropertyPreprocessor`   | Replaces any strings of the form ${VAR} with the system property $VAR if defined. These replacement strings can occur between other strings.<br/><br/>For example `debug: ${DEBUG}` would result in debug being assigned the value `true` assuming the application had been started with `-Ddebug=true`                                                                                                                                 |\n698-| `RandomPreprocessor`           | Inserts random strings into the config. See the section on Random Preprocessor for syntax.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                              |\n--\n710-| Preprocessor                    | Function                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                               |\n711-|:--------------------------------|:-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|\n712:| `AwsSecretsManagerPreprocessor` | Replaces strings of the form awssm://key by looking up the value of 'key' from [AWS Secrets Manager](https://aws.amazon.com/secrets-manager/).<br/><br/>This preprocessor requires the `hoplite-aws` module to be added to the classpath.                                                                              |\n713:| `AzureKeyVaultPreprocessor`     | Replaces strings of the form azurekeyvault://key by looking up the value of 'key' from [Azure Key Vault](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/key-vault/).<br/><br/>This preprocessor requires the `hoplite-azure` module to be added to the classpath.                                                              |\n714:| `ParameterStorePreprocessor`    | Replaces strings of the form ${ssm:key} by looking up the value of 'key' from the [AWS Systems Manager Parameter Store](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/systems-manager/latest/userguide/systems-manager-parameter-store.html).<br/><br/>This preprocessor requires the `hoplite-aws` module to be added to the classpath. |\n715-| `ConsulConfigPreprocessor`      | Replaces strings of the form consul://key by looking up the value of 'key' from a [Consul](https://www.consul.io/) server.<br/><br/>This preprocessor requires the `hoplite-consul` module to be added to the classpath.                                                                                               |\n716-| `VaultSecretPreprocessor`       | Replaces strings of the form vault://key by looking up the value of 'key' from a [Vault](https://www.vaultproject.io/) instance.<br/><br/>This preprocessor requires the `hoplite-vault` module to be added to the classpath.                                                                                          |\n--\n753-\n754-```kotlin\n755:val config = ConfigLoaderBuilder.default()\n756-  .addPreprocessor(SecretFilesPreprocessor(Path.of(\"/run/secrets\")))\n757:  .addResourceSource(\"/application.yml\")\n758-  .build()\n759-  .loadConfigOrThrow<MyConfig>()\n--\n800-If you marshall your config to a String using a reflection based tool like Jackson, it will still be able to see the underlying value.\n801-In these cases, you would need to register a custom serializer.\n802:For the Jackson project, a `HopliteModule` object is available in the `hoplite-json` module.\n803-Register this with your Jackson mapper, like `mapper.registerModule(HopliteModule)` and then `Masked` values will be ouputted into Json as \"****\"\n804-\n--\n973-\n974-// create our config loader which will parse config when invoked\n975:val loader = ConfigLoaderBuilder.default()\n976-  .addSource(PropertySource.resource(\"/application.yml\"))\n977-  .build()\n--\n1003-## Add on Modules\n1004-\n1005:Hoplite makes available several other modules that add functionality outside of the main core module. They are in\n1006-seperate modules because they bring in dependencies from those projects and so the modules are optional.\n1007-\n--\n1009-|:------------------------------|:--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|\n1010-| hoplite-arrow                 | Provides decoders for common arrow types                                                                |\n1011:| hoplite-aws                   | Provides decoders for aws `Region` type and a preprocessor for AWS Secrets Manager and Parameter Store. |\n1012:| hoplite-aws2                  | Provides decoders for aws `Region` type using the AWS v2 SDK.                                           |\n1013:| hoplite-azure                 | Provides a preprocessor for retreiving values from Azure Key Vault.                                     |\n1014-| hoplite-consul                | Provides a preprocessor for retreiving values from a Consul instance.                                   |\n1015-| hoplite-datetime              | Provides decoders for [kotlinx datetime](https://github.com/Kotlin/kotlinx-datetime).                   |\n"}], "isError": false, "timestamp": 1782645483436}}
