se", "timestamp": 1782645481109, "responseId": "resp_0106925b7376a3df016a4102e9a29c8193b659814dbe69e0d6"}, "toolResults": [{"role": "toolResult", "toolCallId": "call_XzcToj2z1VwVCesDIbN98i0o|fc_0106925b7376a3df016a4102ea9f0c8193851725894b0286c1", "toolName": "bash", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "7-\n8-![master](https://github.com/sksamuel/hoplite/workflows/master/badge.svg)\n9:[<img src=\"https://img.shields.io/maven-central/v/com.sksamuel.hoplite/hoplite-core.svg?label=latest%20release\"/>](http://search.maven.org/#search%7Cga%7C1%7Choplite)\n10:[<img src=\"https://img.shields.io/maven-metadata/v?metadataUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fcentral.sonatype.com%2Frepository%2Fmaven-snapshots%2Fcom%2Fsksamuel%2Fhoplite%2Fhoplite-core%2Fmaven-metadata.xml&strategy=highestVersion&label=maven-snapshot\">](https://central.sonatype.com/repository/maven-snapshots/com/sksamuel/hoplite/hoplite-core/maven-metadata.xml)\n11-\n12-## Features\n13-\n14-- **Multiple formats:** Write your configuration in [several formats](#supported-formats): Yaml, JSON, Toml, Hocon, or\n15:  Java .props files or even mix and match formats in the same system.\n16:- **Property Sources:** Per-system overrides are possible from JVM system properties,\n17:  environment variables, JNDI or a per-user local config file.\n18-- **Batteries included:** Support for many [standard types](#decoders) such as primitives, enums, dates, collection\n19-  types, inline classes, uuids, nullable types, as well as popular Kotlin third party library types such\n--\n23-- **Cascading:** Config files can be [stacked](#cascading-config). Start with a default file and then layer new\n24-  configurations on top. When resolving config, lookup of values falls through to the first file that contains a\n25:  definition. Can be used to have a default config file and then an environment specific file.\n26-- **Beautiful errors:** Fail fast at runtime, with [beautiful errors](#beautiful-errors) showing exactly what went wrong and where.\n27-- **Preprocessors:** Support for several [preprocessors](https://github.com/sksamuel/hoplite#preprocessors) that will\n28:  replace placeholders with values resolved from external configs, such as AWS Secrets Manager, Azure KeyVault and so on.\n29-- **Reloadable config:** Trigger config [reloads](#reloadable-config) on a fixed interval or in response to external\n30-  events such as consul value changes.\n--\n41-\n42-```groovy\n43:implementation 'com.sksamuel.hoplite:hoplite-core:<version>'\n44-```\n45-\n--\n49-You should create a top level class which can be named simply Config, or ProjectNameConfig. This class then defines a field for each config value you need. It can include nested data classes for grouping together related configs.\n50-\n51:For example, if we had a project that needed database config, config for an embedded HTTP server, and a field which contained which environment we were running in (staging, QA, production etc), then we may define our classes like this:\n52-\n53-```kotlin\n--\n57-```\n58-\n59:For our staging environment, we may create a YAML (or Json, etc) file called `application-staging.yaml`.\n60-The name doesn't matter, you can use any convention you wish.\n61-\n--\n77-\n78-```kotlin\n79:val config = ConfigLoaderBuilder.default()\n80:               .addResourceSource(\"/application-staging.yml\")\n81-               .build()\n82-               .loadConfigOrThrow<Config>()\n--\n95-enable reports, add preprocessors and more.\n96-\n97:To create a default builder, use `ConfigLoaderBuilder.default()` and after adding your sources, call `build`.\n98-Here is an example:\n99-\n100-```kotlin\n101:ConfigLoaderBuilder.default()\n102:  .addResourceSource(\"/application-prod.yml\")\n103:  .addResourceSource(\"/reference.json\")\n104-  .build()\n105-  .loadConfigOrThrow<MyConfig>()\n--\n142-\n143-```kotlin\n144:val configBinder = ConfigLoaderBuilder.default()\n145:  .addResourceSource(\"/application-prod.yml\")\n146:  .addResourceSource(\"/reference.json\")\n147-  .build()\n148-  .configBinder()\n--\n194-```\n195-\n196:## Supported Formats\n197-\n198-Hoplite supports config files in several formats. You can mix and match formats if you really want to.\n--\n202-| Format                                                              | Module                                                             | File Extensions     |\n203-|:--------------------------------------------------------------------|:-------------------------------------------------------------------|:--------------------|\n204:| [Json](https://www.json.org/)                                       | [`hoplite-json`](https://search.maven.org/search?q=hoplite-json)   | .json               |\n205:| [Yaml](https://yaml.org/) Note: Yaml files are limited 3mb in size. | [`hoplite-yaml`](https://search.maven.org/search?q=hoplite-yaml)   | .yml, .yaml         |\n206-| [Toml](https://github.com/toml-lang/toml)                           | [`hoplite-toml`](https://search.maven.org/search?q=hoplite-toml)   | .toml               |\n207-| [Hocon](https://github.com/lightbend/config)                        | [`hoplite-hocon`](https://search.maven.org/search?q=hoplite-hocon) | .conf               |\n208:| Java Properties files                                               | built-in                                                           | .props, .properties |\n209-\n210-If you wish to add another format you can extend `Parser` and provide an instance of that implementation to\n--\n215-like this:\n216-\n217:`ConfigLoaderBuilder.default().addParser(\"data\", YamlParser).build()`\n218-\n219-### Note: fatJar/shadowJar\n--\n235-### EnvironmentVariablesPropertySource\n236-\n237:The `EnvironmentVariablesPropertySource` reads config from environment variables.\n238:This property source maps environment variable names to config properties via idiomatic conventions for environment variables.\n239:Env vars are idiomatically UPPERCASE and [contain only](https://pubs.opengroup.org/onlinepubs/000095399/basedefs/xbd_chap08.html) letters (`A` to `Z`), digits (`0` to `9`), and the underscore (`_`) character.\n240-\n241:Hoplite's binding rules align with [Spring Boot's relaxed binding for environment variables](https://docs.spring.io/spring-boot/reference/features/external-config.html#features.external-config.typesafe-configuration-properties.relaxed-binding.environment-variables) so that the same env vars can drive both kinds of app:\n242-\n243-| Rule | Env var | Binds to |\n244-|------|---------|----------|\n245:| Dots in property paths become underscores | `TOPIC_NAME` | `topic.name` |\n246-| Matching is case-insensitive — env vars uppercase, fields can be camelCase | `SPRING_MAIN_LOGSTARTUPINFO` | `spring.main.logStartupInfo` |\n247:| Dashes in property paths are removed (not replaced with underscores) | `LOGSTARTUPINFO` | `log-startup-info` (e.g. via `@ConfigAlias`) |\n248:| List/array indices are surrounded by underscores | `ITEMS_0`, `ITEMS_1` | `items: List<String>` |\n249-| List of nested objects | `SERVICE_0_OTHER`, `SERVICE_1_OTHER` | `service: List<Service(other = ...)>` |\n250-| Trailing path segment names a map key | `LABELS_ENV`, `LABELS_REGION` | `labels: Map<String, String>` |\n--\n264-### SystemPropertiesPropertySource\n265-\n266:The `SystemPropertiesPropertySource` provides config through system properties that are prefixed with `config.override.`.\n267-For example, starting your JVM with `-Dconfig.override.database.name` would override a config key of `database.name` residing in a file.\n268-\n269-The prefix may be customized by passing a `prefix` argument to the constructor, or set to an empty string to expose\n270:all system properties.\n271-\n272-\n--\n297-\n298-```kotlin\n299:ConfigLoaderBuilder.default()\n300:   .addResourceSource(\"/config.json\")\n301-   .build()\n302-   .loadConfigOrThrow<MyConfig>()\n--\n306-\n307-```kotlin\n308:ConfigLoaderBuilder.default()\n309:  .addResourceSource(\"/missing.yml\", optional = true)\n310:  .addResourceSource(\"/config.json\")\n311-  .build()\n312-  .loadConfigOrThrow<MyConfig>()\n--\n319-\n320-```kotlin\n321:ConfigLoaderBuilder.default()\n322-   .addSource(JsonPropertySource(\"\"\" { \"database\": \"localhost\", \"port\": 1234 } \"\"\"))\n323-   .build()\n--\n330-\n331-```kotlin\n332:ConfigLoaderBuilder.default()\n333-   .addSource(YamlPropertySource(\n334-     \"\"\"\n--\n345-\n346-```kotlin\n347:ConfigLoaderBuilder.default()\n348-  .addSource(TomlPropertySource(\n349-    \"\"\"\n--\n360-\n361-```kotlin\n362:ConfigLoaderBuilder.default()\n363-  .addSource(PropsPropertySource(myProps))\n364-  .build()\n--\n468-\n469-```kotlin\n470:ConfigLoaderBuilder.default()\n471:  .addResourceSource(\"/config-prd.yml\", true)\n472:  .addResourceSource(\"/config.yml\")\n473-  .strict()\n474-  .build()\n--\n612-| **Arrow**                               | Requires `hoplite-arrow` module                                                                                                                                                                             |\n613-| `arrow.data.NonEmptyList<A>`            | Converts arrays into a `NonEmptyList<A>` if the array is non empty. If the array is empty then an error is raised.                                                                                          |\n614:| `arrow.core.Option<A>`                  | A `None` is used for null or undefined values, and present values are converted to a `Some<A>`.                                                                                                             |\n615:| `arrow.core.Tuple2<A,B>`                | Converts an array of two elements into an instance of `Tuple2<A,B>`.  Will fail if the array does not have exactly two elements.                                                                            |\n616:| `arrow.core.Tuple3<A,B,C>`              | Converts an array of three elements into an instance of `Tuple3<A,B,C>`. Will fail if the array does not 